      TRAs
   =20
 =20
One strange piece of market inefficiency is that public markets supposedly =
undervalue tax assets.
  [1]
=C2=A0So a private equity firm will sometimes take a company private and th=
en run it in a way that generates lots of tax deductions, lots of tax credi=
ts and net operating losses and depreciation and amortization that will off=
set future taxable income. And they will look at the company and see that i=
t has, say, an operating business worth $100=C2=A0and tax assets that will =
generate $5 per year of tax savings,
  [2]
=C2=A0and they will be happy.But then they will want to take it public, and=
 they will go to public investors and say =E2=80=9Chow much would you pay u=
s for this company,=E2=80=9D and the public investors will say =E2=80=9C$10=
0,=E2=80=9D and the private equity firm will say =E2=80=9Csure the business=
 is worth $100, but we=E2=80=99ve got all these tax benefits, like $5 per y=
ear of tax benefits, surely that=E2=80=99s worth like $125 total?=E2=80=9D =
And the public investors will say =E2=80=9Cno, we don=E2=80=99t understand =
taxes, we don=E2=80=99t care about that stuff, we=E2=80=99ll pay you $100.=
=E2=80=9DAnd so the private equity owner will say =E2=80=9COkay fine look. =
If you don=E2=80=99t care about the tax benefits, we will keep them. We=E2=
=80=99ll sell you part of the company =E2=80=94=C2=A0we=E2=80=99ll do an in=
itial public offering and sell stock that entitles you to a share of the bu=
siness=E2=80=99s profits =E2=80=94=C2=A0but we=E2=80=99ll keep all of the t=
ax benefits. The company will just run its business normally and calculate =
its pretax profits without considering all of the tax benefits that we=E2=
=80=99ve baked into the company, and then it will set aside 21% of those pr=
ofits for taxes. If the company makes $40 in a year, it will set aside $8.2=
0 for taxes. And then it will use its tax deductions and figure out the tax=
 it=C2=A0actually=C2=A0owes, and it will pay that to the government, and pa=
y the rest to us. If the actual tax bill is $3.20, we=E2=80=99ll keep the o=
ther $5.=E2=80=9D And the public investors will say =E2=80=9Csure that=E2=
=80=99s fine, we don=E2=80=99t want the tax benefits anyway, we=E2=80=99ll =
pay you $100 for the company without them.=E2=80=9D The tax benefits will s=
tay with the people =E2=80=94=C2=A0the private equity firm =E2=80=94=C2=A0w=
ho value them.This trade =E2=80=94=C2=A0paying the tax benefits to the pre-=
IPO owners =E2=80=94=C2=A0is called a =E2=80=9Ctax receivable agreement,=E2=
=80=9D or TRA. Ordinarily the way it works is that, before the IPO, the com=
pany identifies some existing tax assets that will reduce its taxable incom=
e in the future, and it agrees to pay some large fraction =E2=80=94=C2=A0of=
ten 85% or 90% =E2=80=94=C2=A0of those benefits to the pre-IPO owner for so=
me period of time, often 15 years. (The company keeps some of the benefits,=
 to align incentives.) We have talked about TRAs a few times before. Last y=
ear, we talked about a takeover battle involving Sculptor Capital Managemen=
t Inc., a hedge fund firm. Before it went public, Sculptor was a partnershi=
p, and when the partners converted their partnership interests into public-=
company shares they (1) owed taxes personally but (2) generated tax deducti=
ons for the company; Sculptor signed a TRA agreeing to give them 85% of tho=
se tax deductions back.
  [3]
=C2=A0And earlier this year we discussed Parallaxes Capital, an investment =
firm that buys TRAs, sometimes from people who didn=E2=80=99t know they eve=
n had a TRA.As I mentioned when we discussed Parallaxes, most TRAs are paid=
 out early if the company is acquired. If the company goes public, and thre=
e years later it is acquired, it can=E2=80=99t really keep paying the tax b=
enefits to the pre-IPO owner, so it will just pay them all out at once in a=
 lump sum. The lump sum is something like =E2=80=9Cif we save $5 of taxes e=
ach year for the remaining 12 years of the TRA, that=E2=80=99s $60 of savin=
gs over 12 years, and discounted at 6.5% it=E2=80=99s about $40.=E2=80=9D S=
o the company will cash out the TRA for $40.This is generally quite favorab=
le for the TRA holder. For one thing, the payments tend to be discounted at=
 a pretty favorable rate, making the lump sum more valuable than getting th=
e payments over time.
  [4]
=C2=A0Also, though, the calculation is normally made using favorable assump=
tions: In particular, it normally assumes that the company will be able to=
=C2=A0use=C2=A0all of the tax benefits. (If in fact the company loses money=
 in Year 12, it will not get any tax benefits and won=E2=80=99t pay anythin=
g out on the TRA, but the lump-sum calculation just assumes that the compan=
y will make plenty of income in all of the future years.)And so an acquisit=
ion is=C2=A0better=C2=A0for the TRA holder than it is for all the other sha=
reholders. If the company sells itself, then the public shareholders get pa=
id for their shares, but the pre-IPO shareholder will get paid for its shar=
es and will also get cashed out for its TRA. The TRA payment can be=C2=A0 m=
ore valuable than the payment for the shares. And in many cases the TRA hol=
der =E2=80=94=C2=A0the company=E2=80=99s founder, perhaps, or the private e=
quity firm that took it public =E2=80=94=C2=A0will also be a big shareholde=
r of the public company, often with board seats and control of the company.=
 And so the TRA holder might want to sell, and it might have the ability to=
=C2=A0make the company sell. It might not care that much about the price. E=
ven if the company is worth more to other shareholders=C2=A0on its own, it =
might be worth more=C2=A0to its TRA holder=C2=A0in a sale.
  [5]
In particular, starting in 2018, the US federal corporate tax rate went dow=
n from 35% to 21%, which made TRA payments less valuable: A $1 tax deductio=
n would now generate only 21 cents of tax savings, rather than 35 cents. Th=
is was good for companies =E2=80=94=C2=A0they would pay less tax,=C2=A0and=
=C2=A0pay less under their TRAs =E2=80=94=C2=A0but bad for the TRA holders,=
 who would get paid less on their TRAs. Accelerating the TRA =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0getting the cash now, rather than waiting 15 years =E2=80=94=C2=A0became=
 more attractive.Did that cause private equity firms to dump their public p=
ortfolio companies to accelerate their TRAs? Eh, maybe a little.=C2=A0Here =
is a Cleary Gottlieb Steen & Hamilton LLP client memo from last week:In a M=
ay 31, 2024 opinion, the Delaware Court of Chancery denied a motion to dism=
iss a complaint challenging the sale of a public company with a controlling=
 private equity sponsor to an unrelated, arms-length buyer, finding that th=
e sale was potentially tainted by conflicts of interest.=C2=A0In particular=
, the court found that it was reasonably conceivable that the private equit=
y sponsor=E2=80=99s receipt of an early termination payment under a tax rec=
eivable agreement put into place upon the target company=E2=80=99s initial =
public offering was a material nonratable benefit, which may have led the s=
ponsor to push for a sale (which would trigger the early termination paymen=
t), even if remaining a standalone company would have been better for the m=
inority stockholders.=C2=A0Here is the opinion. Lone Star Funds, a private =
equity firm, bought Foundation Building Materials in 2015. In 2017, it took=
 Foundation public again, with a TRA giving Lone Star 90% of the benefits f=
rom its pre-IPO tax assets. The TRA provided that, if Foundation was acquir=
ed, Lone Star=C2=A0 could terminate the TRA and get a lump-sum payment calc=
ulated (1) using a low discount rate
  [6]
 and (2) assuming that Foundation could use all of the tax benefits every y=
ear. Lone Star held a majority of the stock and board seats after the IPO.L=
ater in 2017, the corporate tax rate was cut from 35% to 21% and, says the =
judge:It is reasonable to infer that after the Tax Act, Lone Star recognize=
d that it could generate more value for itself by selling the Company and=
=C2=A0 triggering an Early Termination Payment than by managing the Company=
 as an independent entity, receiving annual payments under the Tax Agreemen=
t, and selling off its position over time. Consistent with that inference, =
in early 2018, Lone Star began to explore its options for exiting the Compa=
ny.=C2=A0The company looked for buyers. Understanding that the TRA was a co=
nflict of interest, it set up a special committee of independent directors =
to make sure that any deal was fair to shareholders, but the judge conclude=
d it wasn=E2=80=99t good enough:Well after the sale process was underway, t=
he board created a special committee to address the conflict created by the=
 early termination payment. The board charged the committee with determinin=
g whether a sale was advisable and gave the committee the power to say =E2=
=80=9Cno.=E2=80=9D Despite those powers and its charge, the committee was p=
assive. Its members repeatedly went months without convening, including dur=
ing busy periods when the fund=E2=80=99s representatives were negotiating t=
he terms of a sale. The committee also took specific actions that smack of =
deference to the fund.The sale process actually seems fine =E2=80=94=C2=A0t=
hey contacted a bunch of potential buyers, got multiple bids, played them o=
ff against each other and ultimately took the highest one, $19.25 per share=
 in cash, a 27% premium to the stock=E2=80=99s trading price=C2=A0=E2=80=94=
=C2=A0but the judge decided that=C2=A0the decision to sell itself=C2=A0coul=
d have been conflicted. =E2=80=9CUnder this theory, Lone Star must prove th=
at the Merger was entirely fair relative to the alternative of operating th=
e Company as a standalone entity.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s possible that the c=
ompany was worth more than $19.25 per share=C2=A0to shareholders, but that =
Lone Star took the deal to cash out its TRA. Lone Star was Foundation=E2=80=
=99s biggest shareholder, but it didn=E2=80=99t just own Foundation=E2=80=
=99s business. It also owned its tax savings, and it apparently valued thos=
e more than the other shareholders did.
