I wrote yesterday that GameStop is a meme stock, yes, but it is also an ope=
rating business with an experienced successful chief executive officer and =
a bunch of stores that sell videogames. You could, and people do, have some=
 thesis about how it will transform its business to become profitable and g=
rowing. Fine. On the other hand, the Financial Times reports:GameStop=E2=80=
=99s ecommerce strategy has faltered, its bricks-and-mortar store count is =
shrinking and its sales are in a multiyear slide. But one measure of the vi=
deo game retailer is a picture of health: the amount of cash in its account=
s.The company at the centre of the 2021 meme-stock frenzy has once again ca=
ptivated Wall Street after its shares soared in the past month on little mo=
re than the re-emergence of the influential social media fan known as Roari=
ng Kitty.=C2=A0Management took advantage of its sudden increase in valuatio=
n to sell 45mn shares and raise $933mn. Last Friday GameStop alerted invest=
ors to a potential sale of another 75mn shares, which at Monday=E2=80=99s c=
losing price would be worth $1.9bn.In doing so, the company followed a well=
-worn meme stock playbook of recent years, using their shortlived popularit=
y to raise cash. The mystery is where it will put all the money, which stan=
ds at $2bn.That $2 billion, though, is before the offering it launched last=
 Friday.=C2=A0Last week, GameStop released its financial statements as of M=
ay 4, which included almost $1.1 billion of cash and marketable securities.=
 Add the $933 million it raised by selling stock in May and you get to abou=
t $2 billion. It has a new at-the-market offering of 75 million shares goin=
g on, starting last Friday, and my assumption is that it is selling that st=
ock as fast as possible. Which is pretty fast: GameStop traded 279 million =
shares on Friday and 131=C2=A0million yesterday; if it=E2=80=99s selling 10=
% of volume GameStop could be more than halfway done by now. On aggressive =
but plausible assumptions, GameStop could have sold about 41 million more s=
hares for about $1.3 billion by the end of yesterday.
  [7]
 That would give it a cash pile of about $3.3 billion, and a market capital=
ization, as of yesterday=E2=80=99s close, of $9.7 billion.
  [8]
=C2=A0If it finishes selling all 75 million shares in the next few days, at=
 around the current stock price, it will have about $4.2 billion of cash an=
d a market cap of about $10.6 billion.
  [9]
Yesterday=E2=80=99s closing price was $24.83 per share. The stock closed at=
 a high of $48.75 on May 14, shortly after Roaring Kitty (Keith Gill) retur=
ned to social media. Before that, though, it was lower. It closed as low as=
 $10.01 per share in April. At $10.01 per share,=C2=A0GameStop=E2=80=99s ma=
rket capitalization would be about $4.3=C2=A0billion.
  [10]
My point here is that $4.2 billion and $4.3 billion are not=C2=A0that=C2=A0=
different? One thing that GameStop could do with its pile of cash is=C2=A0b=
uy (almost) all of its own stock.Obviously I=E2=80=99m kidding. You can=E2=
=80=99t do that, for various reasons, the main one being that if GameStop t=
ried to buy all of its own stock that would push the price up a lot. On the=
 other hand =E2=80=A6=C2=A0like, kind of, right? Here is a scenario that I =
do not think is=C2=A0that crazy:=09Keith Gill stops posting, and/or his pos=
ts stop having much effect. His Friday YouTube livestream seems to have bee=
n=C2=A0bad=C2=A0for GameStop=E2=80=99s stock price. Since then, his posts o=
n X have included a man with a duffel bag=C2=A0(and a cat=E2=80=99s head?) =
seeming to slump away down a city street, and a cartoon man looking in a mi=
rror saying =E2=80=9CYou=C2=A0were=C2=A0a billionaire.=E2=80=9D Maybe he wi=
ll give up, quietly sell his stock and enjoy his wealth? I am certainly not=
 predicting this; I=E2=80=99m just saying it is a thing that=C2=A0could hap=
pen.=09GameStop will=C2=A0not=C2=A0announce any transformative business ini=
tiatives or huge profits. It preannounced earnings last week, and they were=
 disappointing.=09Without any new catalysts from Roaring Kitty or the compa=
ny, the stock will slide to roughly where it was in April.
  [11]
=09GameStop will announce a stock buyback, buy back all 120 million shares =
it sold this year for less than it sold them for, bank probably hundreds of=
 millions of dollars of profit and support the stock price.=09Repeat this e=
very year or so and you have a profitable business of selling stock to peop=
le during moments of euphoria and buying it back cheaply when they lose int=
erest.=09Never mind the videogames.This is so stupid, I=E2=80=99m sorry. Th=
is can=E2=80=99t really work. Except that it can? This, I suppose, is the e=
nd state of meme stocks: Turn the stock into a pure trading token, unrelate=
d to any actual business of the company, and turn=C2=A0the company=C2=A0int=
o a pure vehicle for trading the stock. Sell stock when it's high, buy it b=
ack when it=E2=80=99s low, forget about the business and drift on the waves=
 of social media sentiment.This won=E2=80=99t happen, though. Probably they=
=E2=80=99ll spend all that cash on something =E2=80=94 doing an acquisition=
, building out an online platform, buying crypto, something. But will that =
strategy be=C2=A0better=C2=A0than spending the money on buying back the sto=
ck when the price goes down?
