   =20
 =20
How many tech startups do you think do stuff like this?Raz also touted the =
quantity and quality of Joonko=E2=80=99s customer base on public media webs=
ites while she was raising money for Joonko. For example, on January 6, 202=
3, Raz claimed in a public YouTube video that Joonko was now working with o=
ver 200 customers and highlighted Purported Customers A, B, and C as Joonko=
=E2=80=99s exemplary customer companies.Raz=E2=80=99s public LinkedIn profi=
le as of June 28, 2023 listed several Fortune 500 companies as part of Joon=
ko=E2=80=99s customer base. ...Joonko had far fewer than 200 customers and =
its customer base did not include Purported Customers A, B, or C, or the co=
mpanies listed in Raz=E2=80=99s LinkedIn profile.Or this?In an email to Inv=
estor B and likely others in November 2019, Joonko stated, with Raz=E2=80=
=99s knowledge, that it had =E2=80=9Cmore than 40,000 candidates in [its] t=
alent pool.=E2=80=9D =E2=80=A6 Joonko had significantly fewer, if any, cand=
idates on its=C2=A0platform in 2019.Or this?The Round B Presentation also i=
ncluded the following fake testimonials:a. a fake testimonial from Purporte=
d Customer A stating, =E2=80=9CJoonko has been immeasurably effective in he=
lping our team attract more diverse candidates, by bringing them directly t=
o our recruiters and keeping track of our hiring progress while advancing t=
hese candidates=E2=80=9D;b. a fake testimonial from Purported Customer C st=
ating, =E2=80=9CDiversity is at the heart of our culture and Joonko helped =
us turn this aspiration to a successful reality=E2=80=9D; andc. a fake test=
imonial from Purported Customer D stating, =E2=80=9CI love the fact that I =
don=E2=80=99t need another dashboard and that relevant candidates are simpl=
y flowing into our [Applicant Tracking System], saving me so much time on s=
ourcing. Because of Joonko, I was able to get back to what really matters =
=E2=80=93 hiring great talent.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0Those are all from the complai=
nt in a US Securities and Exchange Commission lawsuit against Ilit Raz, the=
 founder of a startup called Joonko, which purportedly used artificial inte=
lligence to help companies hire diverse job candidates. Federal prosecutors=
 also brought a criminal case. There is plenty of egregious stuff here; fro=
m the criminal case:In or about 2023, a Joonko investor (=E2=80=9CInvestor-=
1=E2=80=9D) became suspicious about Joonko=E2=80=99s performance and reques=
ted certain information from Joonko, including bank statements. =C2=A0In re=
sponse, on or about April 3, 2023, RAZ emailed Investor-1 a purported Joonk=
o bank statement, which depicted that the company had an average balance of=
 over $5,000,000. =C2=A0In truth and in fact, and as RAZ well knew, the ban=
k records that RAZ emailed to Investor-1 were forged, and the actual bank r=
ecords showed that Joonko=E2=80=99s true account balance was millions of do=
llars lower. =C2=A0Less than a week later, on or about April 8, 2023, RAZ e=
mailed Investor-1 a set of purported purchase orders for Joonko customers. =
=C2=A0RAZ knew that many of the purchase orders she emailed to Investor-1 w=
ere fictitious, contained forged signatures, and were executed on behalf of=
 purported customers that had no business relationship with Joonko.You can=
=E2=80=99t forge bank statements or signatures on purchase orders! That=E2=
=80=99s bad. On the other hand, is Raz the first startup CEO to write fake =
customer=C2=A0testimonials? Is she the first startup CEO to be a bit aspira=
tional=C2=A0on her LinkedIn profile?=C2=A0My sense has always been that, if=
 you are a public company, everything is securities fraud: You have to be s=
crupulously truthful in all of your public communications, and if investors=
 can find the slightest arguable misstatement they will sue you for securit=
ies fraud. And if you are actually lying about your customers and revenue, =
you will go to prison.At private startups, on the other hand, the rules hav=
e usually been a bit laxer. Not as a legal matter, but as a practical matte=
r. Fewer people see your statements, for one thing. (They=E2=80=99re not pu=
blic.) Those people are more likely to be sympathetic venture capitalists, =
who probably won=E2=80=99t sue you or turn you in to the authorities if you=
=E2=80=99re lying. Also, your stock does not trade continuously, so nobody =
can say =E2=80=9CI was deceived by that interview you did and bought your s=
tock.=E2=80=9D=C2=A0The stock only trades when you sell it in defined fundr=
aising rounds, so you can take some liberties on your LinkedIn as long as y=
ou walk them back in the official investor presentations. (Not legal advice=
!)But my sense is also that private markets are the new public markets: As =
startups raise millions of dollars from institutions and individuals, and s=
tay private longer, it does make more sense that the rules of public market=
s increasingly apply to private ones. These days, if you puff up your Linke=
dIn as a startup CEO, that can get you in just as much trouble as it would =
if you were a public-company CEO.
