10px;">
<table class=3D"header" width=3D"100%" border=3D"0" cellspacing=3D"0" cellp=
adding=3D"0">
<tr>
<td class=3D"body-header-container" style=3D"border-collapse: collapse; mso=
-table-lspace: 0pt; mso-table-rspace: 0pt;">
<h2 style=3D"font-weight: bold; font-family: &quot;Arial Black&quot;, Arial=
, Helvetica, sans-serif; letter-spacing: -1px; font-size: 20px; border-bott=
om-width: 1px; border-bottom-style: dotted; margin: 0px; padding: 16px 0px =
5px;">TRAs</h2>
</td>
</tr>
</table><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">One strange piece of market inefficien=
cy is that public markets supposedly undervalue tax assets.<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-1" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[1]</span>
</a>=C2=A0So a private equity firm will sometimes take a company private an=
d then run it in a way that generates lots of tax deductions, lots of tax c=
redits and net operating losses and depreciation and amortization that will=
 offset future taxable income. And they will look at the company and see th=
at it has, say, an operating business worth $100=C2=A0and tax assets that w=
ill generate $5 per year of tax savings,<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D=
"#footnote-2" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; bo=
rder-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: =
none !important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-=
block;">
<span>[2]</span>
</a>=C2=A0and they will be happy.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">But then =
they will want to take it public, and they will go to public investors and =
say =E2=80=9Chow much would you pay us for this company,=E2=80=9D and the p=
ublic investors will say =E2=80=9C$100,=E2=80=9D and the private equity fir=
m will say =E2=80=9Csure the business is worth $100, but we=E2=80=99ve got =
all these tax benefits, like $5 per year of tax benefits, surely that=E2=80=
=99s worth like $125 total?=E2=80=9D And the public investors will say =E2=
=80=9Cno, we don=E2=80=99t understand taxes, we don=E2=80=99t care about th=
at stuff, we=E2=80=99ll pay you $100.=E2=80=9D</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px =
0;">And so the private equity owner will say =E2=80=9COkay fine look. If yo=
u don=E2=80=99t care about the tax benefits, we will keep them. We=E2=80=99=
ll sell you part of the company =E2=80=94=C2=A0we=E2=80=99ll do an initial =
public offering and sell stock that entitles you to a share of the business=
=E2=80=99s profits =E2=80=94=C2=A0but we=E2=80=99ll keep all of the tax ben=
efits. The company will just run its business normally and calculate its pr=
etax profits without considering all of the tax benefits that we=E2=80=99ve=
 baked into the company, and then it will set aside 21% of those profits fo=
r taxes. If the company makes $40 in a year, it will set aside $8.20 for ta=
xes. And then it will use its tax deductions and figure out the tax it=C2=
=A0<em>actually=C2=A0</em>owes, and it will pay that to the government, and=
 pay the rest to us. If the actual tax bill is $3.20, we=E2=80=99ll keep th=
e other $5.=E2=80=9D And the public investors will say =E2=80=9Csure that=
=E2=80=99s fine, we don=E2=80=99t want the tax benefits anyway, we=E2=80=99=
ll pay you $100 for the company without them.=E2=80=9D The tax benefits wil=
l stay with the people =E2=80=94=C2=A0the private equity firm =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0who value them.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This trade =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0paying the tax benefits to the pre-IPO owners =E2=80=94=C2=A0is called a=
 =E2=80=9Ctax receivable agreement,=E2=80=9D or TRA. Ordinarily the way it =
works is that, before the IPO, the company identifies some existing tax ass=
ets that will reduce its taxable income in the future, and it agrees to pay=
 some large fraction =E2=80=94=C2=A0often 85% or 90% =E2=80=94=C2=A0of thos=
e benefits to the pre-IPO owner for some period of time, often 15 years. (T=
he company keeps some of the benefits, to align incentives.) We have talked=
 about TRAs a few times before. Last year, <a href=3D"https://link.mail.blo=
ombergbusiness.com/click/35681542.257302/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS=
9vcGluaW9uL2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjMtMDgtMzAvc2N1bHB0b3ItaXMtZnVsbC1vZi1jb25mbGljd=
HM_Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYxMTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNl=
PW5ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNjExJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07=
ceef4b8524a319a23cB379dabc8" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope"=
 target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !importan=
t; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-st=
yle: solid; background-color: #ccc;">we talked about</a> a takeover battle =
involving Sculptor Capital Management Inc., a hedge fund firm. Before it we=
nt public, Sculptor was a partnership, and when the partners converted thei=
r partnership interests into public-company shares they (1) owed taxes pers=
onally but (2) generated tax deductions for the company; Sculptor signed a =
TRA agreeing to give them 85% of those tax deductions back.<a class=3D"foot=
note-index" href=3D"#footnote-3" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: =
none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; bo=
rder-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: transparent !importan=
t; display: inline-block;">
<span>[3]</span>
</a>=C2=A0And earlier this year <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusin=
ess.com/click/35681542.257302/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuYmxvb21iZXJnLmNvbS9vcGluaW9uL=
2FydGljbGVzLzIwMjQtMDEtMDIvZmFrZS1zdXJnZXJpZXMtYXJlLXNlY3VyaXRpZXMtZnJhdWQ_=
Y21waWQ9QkJEMDYxMTI0X01PTkVZU1RVRkYmdXRtX21lZGl1bT1lbWFpbCZ1dG1fc291cmNlPW5=
ld3NsZXR0ZXImdXRtX3Rlcm09MjQwNjExJnV0bV9jYW1wYWlnbj1tb25leXN0dWZm/607f07cee=
f4b8524a319a23cBc974b78f" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" ta=
rget=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; =
border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style=
: solid; background-color: #ccc;">we discussed Parallaxes Capital</a>, an i=
nvestment firm that buys TRAs, sometimes from people who didn=E2=80=99t kno=
w they even had a TRA.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">As I mentioned when =
we discussed Parallaxes, most TRAs are paid out early if the company is acq=
uired. If the company goes public, and three years later it is acquired, it=
 can=E2=80=99t really keep paying the tax benefits to the pre-IPO owner, so=
 it will just pay them all out at once in a lump sum. The lump sum is somet=
hing like =E2=80=9Cif we save $5 of taxes each year for the remaining 12 ye=
ars of the TRA, that=E2=80=99s $60 of savings over 12 years, and discounted=
 at 6.5% it=E2=80=99s about $40.=E2=80=9D So the company will cash out the =
TRA for $40.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">This is generally quite favora=
ble for the TRA holder. For one thing, the payments tend to be discounted a=
t a pretty favorable rate, making the lump sum more valuable than getting t=
he payments over time.<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-4" styl=
e=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width:=
 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; b=
ackground-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[4]</span>
</a>=C2=A0Also, though, the calculation is normally made using favorable as=
sumptions: In particular, it normally assumes that the company will be able=
 to=C2=A0<em>use=C2=A0</em>all of the tax benefits. (If in fact the company=
 loses money in Year 12, it will not get any tax benefits and won=E2=80=99t=
 pay anything out on the TRA, but the lump-sum calculation just assumes tha=
t the company will make plenty of income in all of the future years.)</p><p=
 style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">And so an acquisition is=C2=A0<em>better=C2=A0</=
em>for the TRA holder than it is for all the other shareholders. If the com=
pany sells itself, then the public shareholders get paid for their shares, =
but the pre-IPO shareholder will get paid for its shares and will <em>also =
</em>get cashed out for its TRA. The TRA payment can be=C2=A0 more valuable=
 than the payment for the shares. And in many cases the TRA holder =E2=80=
=94=C2=A0the company=E2=80=99s founder, perhaps, or the private equity firm=
 that took it public =E2=80=94=C2=A0will also be a big shareholder of the p=
ublic company, often with board seats and control of the company. And so th=
e TRA holder might want to sell, and it might have the ability to=C2=A0<em>=
make </em>the company sell. It might not care that much about the price. Ev=
en if the company is worth more <em>to other shareholders=C2=A0</em>on its =
own, it might be worth more=C2=A0<em>to its TRA holder=C2=A0</em>in a sale.=
<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#footnote-5" style=3D"color: #000000; t=
ext-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-co=
lor: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !important; background-color: trans=
parent !important; display: inline-block;">
<span>[5]</span>
</a></p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In particular, starting in 2018, the U=
S federal corporate tax rate <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness=
.com/click/35681542.257302/aHR0cHM6Ly90YXhzdW1tYXJpZXMucHdjLmNvbS91bml0ZWQt=
c3RhdGVzL2NvcnBvcmF0ZS90YXhlcy1vbi1jb3Jwb3JhdGUtaW5jb21l/607f07ceef4b8524a3=
19a23cB5430a419" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_=
blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bo=
ttom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; =
background-color: #ccc;">went down</a> from 35% to 21%, which made TRA paym=
ents less valuable: A $1 tax deduction would now generate only 21 cents of =
tax savings, rather than 35 cents. This was good for companies =E2=80=94=C2=
=A0they would pay less tax,=C2=A0<em>and=C2=A0</em>pay less under their TRA=
s =E2=80=94=C2=A0but bad for the TRA holders, who would get paid less on th=
eir TRAs. Accelerating the TRA =E2=80=94=C2=A0getting the cash now, rather =
than waiting 15 years =E2=80=94=C2=A0became more attractive.</p><p style=3D=
"margin: 16px 0;">Did that cause private equity firms to dump their public =
portfolio companies to accelerate their TRAs? Eh, maybe a little.=C2=A0Here=
 is a Cleary Gottlieb Steen &amp; Hamilton LLP <a href=3D"https://link.mail=
.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35681542.257302/aHR0cHM6Ly9jbGllbnQuY2xlYXJ5Z2=
90dGxpZWIuY29tLzUxLzMzMDEvdXBsb2Fkcy8yMDI0LTA2LTA3LXRyYS1jb25mbGljdHMtZm91b=
mQtdG8tdGFpbnQtcGUtc3BvbnNvci1zLWV4aXQtZGVhbC5wZGY/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23c=
Bc7e590c5" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank"=
 style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-w=
idth: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; backgr=
ound-color: #ccc;">client memo</a> from last week:</p><blockquote><p style=
=3D"margin: 16px 0;">In a May 31, 2024 opinion, the Delaware Court of Chanc=
ery denied a motion to dismiss a complaint challenging the sale of a public=
 company with a controlling private equity sponsor to an unrelated, arms-le=
ngth buyer, finding that the sale was potentially tainted by conflicts of i=
nterest.=C2=A0In particular, the court found that it was reasonably conceiv=
able that the private equity sponsor=E2=80=99s receipt of an early terminat=
ion payment under a tax receivable agreement put into place upon the target=
 company=E2=80=99s initial public offering was a material nonratable benefi=
t, which may have led the sponsor to push for a sale (which would trigger t=
he early termination payment), even if remaining a standalone company would=
 have been better for the minority stockholders.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p s=
tyle=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Here is <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusi=
ness.com/click/35681542.257302/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3VydHMuZGVsYXdhcmUuZ292L09waW5p=
b25zL0Rvd25sb2FkLmFzcHg_aWQ9MzY0ODMw/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB76c3b3c0" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">the opinion</a>. Lone Star Funds, a private equity firm, bought Founda=
tion Building Materials in 2015. In 2017, it <a href=3D"https://link.mail.b=
loombergbusiness.com/click/35681542.257302/aHR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNo=
aXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE2ODg5NDEvMDAwMTE5MzEyNTE3MDQwNDcwL2QzMzY4NThkNDI0YjQ=
uaHRtI3JvbTMzNjg1OF8z/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB50e204fa" itemprop=3D"StoryL=
ink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; tex=
t-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-colo=
r: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #ccc;">took Found=
ation public</a> again, with a TRA giving Lone Star 90% of the benefits fro=
m its pre-IPO tax assets. The TRA provided that, if Foundation was acquired=
, Lone Star=C2=A0 could terminate the TRA and get a lump-sum payment calcul=
ated (1) using a low discount rate<a class=3D"footnote-index" href=3D"#foot=
note-6" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-b=
ottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: none !=
important; background-color: transparent !important; display: inline-block;=
">
<span>[6]</span>
</a> and (2) assuming that Foundation could use all of the tax benefits eve=
ry year. Lone Star held a majority of the stock and board seats after the I=
PO.</p><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Later in 2017, the corporate tax rate w=
as cut from 35% to 21% and, says the judge:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">It is reasonable to infer that after the Tax Act, Lone Star re=
cognized that it could generate more value for itself by selling the Compan=
y and=C2=A0 triggering an Early Termination Payment than by managing the Co=
mpany as an independent entity, receiving annual payments under the Tax Agr=
eement, and selling off its position over time. Consistent with that infere=
nce, in early 2018, Lone Star began to explore its options for exiting the =
Company.=C2=A0</p></blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">The company loo=
ked for buyers. Understanding that the TRA was a conflict of interest, it s=
et up a special committee of independent directors to make sure that any de=
al was fair to shareholders, but the judge concluded it wasn=E2=80=99t good=
 enough:</p><blockquote><p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">Well after the sale pr=
ocess was underway, the board created a special committee to address the co=
nflict created by the early termination payment. The board charged the comm=
ittee with determining whether a sale was advisable and gave the committee =
the power to say =E2=80=9Cno.=E2=80=9D Despite those powers and its charge,=
 the committee was passive. Its members repeatedly went months without conv=
ening, including during busy periods when the fund=E2=80=99s representative=
s were negotiating the terms of a sale. The committee also took specific ac=
tions that smack of deference to the fund.</p></blockquote><p style=3D"marg=
in: 16px 0;">The sale process actually seems fine =E2=80=94=C2=A0they conta=
cted a bunch of potential buyers, got multiple bids, played them off agains=
t each other and ultimately took the highest one, $19.25 per share in cash,=
 <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35681542.257302/a=
HR0cHM6Ly93d3cuc2VjLmdvdi9BcmNoaXZlcy9lZGdhci9kYXRhLzE2ODg5NDEvMDAwMTYyODI4=
MDIwMDE2NDU3L3ByZXNzcmVsZWFzZTExMTUyMDIwLmh0bQ/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cB5b8=
ac153" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" sty=
le=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width=
: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background=
-color: #ccc;">a 27% premium</a> to the stock=E2=80=99s trading price=C2=A0=
=E2=80=94=C2=A0but the judge decided that=C2=A0<em>the decision to sell its=
elf=C2=A0</em>could have been conflicted. =E2=80=9CUnder this theory, Lone =
Star must prove that the Merger was entirely fair relative to the alternati=
ve of operating the Company as a standalone entity.=E2=80=9D It=E2=80=99s p=
ossible that the company was worth more than $19.25 per share=C2=A0<em>to s=
