<div id=3D"footnote-1" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[1] This sounds weird, but as far as I can tel=
l it really is the main rationale for tax receivable agreements: that priva=
te owners are better able to value tax attributes than the public. Here is =
a <a href=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35681542.257302/=
aHR0cHM6Ly9zY2hvbGFyc2hpcC5sYXcudmFuZGVyYmlsdC5lZHUvY2dpL3ZpZXdjb250ZW50LmN=
naT9hcnRpY2xlPTEwMjgmY29udGV4dD12bHI/607f07ceef4b8524a319a23cBf45d5239" ite=
mprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D"_blank" style=3D"colo=
r: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-bottom-width: 1px; bor=
der-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid; background-color: #c=
cc;">2018 Vanderbilt Law Review article</a> about TRAs by Gladriel Shobe, n=
oting that =E2=80=9Cthose who defend TRAs claim that without a TRA, public =
shareholders actually =E2=80=98rip off=E2=80=99 pre-IPO owners because, the=
 argument goes, the public does not pay full value for tax assets in an IPO=
. In other words, the argument in favor of TRAs is that they are an efficie=
nt means of =E2=80=98assuring [pre-IPO owners] receive a fair price for the=
ir business.=E2=80=99=E2=80=9D And: =E2=80=9CPractitioners claim that tax a=
ssets are not priced into IPOs because public company valuations are often =
based on earnings before interest, taxes, depreciation, and amortization (=
=E2=80=98EBITDA=E2=80=99), which excludes both tax assets and tax liabiliti=
es.=E2=80=9D And an Evercore presentation cited in the <a href=3D"https://l=
ink.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35681542.257302/aHR0cHM6Ly9jb3VydHMuZG=
VsYXdhcmUuZ292L09waW5pb25zL0Rvd25sb2FkLmFzcHg_aWQ9MzY0ODMw/607f07ceef4b8524=
a319a23cC76c3b3c0" itemprop=3D"StoryLink" itemscope=3D"itemscope" target=3D=
"_blank" style=3D"color: #000000; text-decoration: none !important; border-=
bottom-width: 1px; border-bottom-color: #000000; border-bottom-style: solid=
; background-color: #ccc;">Foundation opinion</a> (discussed below) said: =
=E2=80=9CThere is limited evidence that public  shareholders typically adju=
st the price they are willing to pay for shares in a public company due to =
the presence of a TRA. =E2=80=A6 Pre-IPO  shareholders generally believe in=
vestors tend to ignore tax attributes =E2=80=A6 [so a TRA] enables the sell=
ing shareholder to retain those benefits.=E2=80=9D To be fair, as in the Sc=
ulptor case, there is another rationale for TRAs, which is basically that i=
f you own partnership units in an Up-C company then your conversion to corp=
orate shares generates taxes for you and tax assets for the company, and th=
e TRA sort of makes you whole.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-2" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[2] Don=E2=80=99t take this too seriously. Wha=
t I mean is something like =E2=80=9Ca business that is worth $100 to equity=
 holders on an after-tax basis assuming full taxation of future income, plu=
s tax benefits that will in fact reduce the taxation of that future income =
by $5 per year.=E2=80=9D</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-3" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[3] This simplifies things =E2=80=94 particula=
rly the timing; they didn=E2=80=99t convert to corporate shares at the IPO =
=E2=80=94 but that=E2=80=99s the basic idea.</p>
</div>
<div id=3D"footnote-4" class=3D"footnote-content" style=3D"font-style: ital=
ic;">
<p style=3D"margin: 16px 0;">[4] Parallaxes, for instance, reportedly <a hr=
ef=3D"https://link.mail.bloombergbusiness.com/click/35681542.257302/aHR0cHM=
6Ly93d3cud3NqLmNvbS9maW5hbmNlL2ludmVzdGluZy90YXgtd2hpei1zdHJhbmdlLWh1c3RsZS=
